## AI-Assisted

## Apply project-wide GitHub security/policy settings to the source
## organizations (Kicksecure, Whonix). Idempotent and apply-only.
## Run `dm-github-policy --help` for the full settings list and
## reasoning.

set -o errexit
set -o nounset
set -o pipefail
set -o errtrace
shopt -s inherit_errexit
shopt -s shift_verbose

if ! command -v github-org-fork >/dev/null 2>&1; then
   printf 'error: github-org-fork not found on PATH (developer-meta-files install incomplete).\n' >&2
   exit 1
fi
# shellcheck source=/usr/libexec/developer-meta-files/github-org-lib.bsh
source /usr/libexec/developer-meta-files/github-org-lib.bsh

## Production list (commented out while testing on org-ai-assisted):
# readonly ORGS=( 'Kicksecure' 'Whonix' )
readonly ORGS=( 'org-ai-assisted' )
readonly POLICY_JOBS=4
readonly RULESET_NAME_BRANCH='dm-github-policy default-branch protection'
readonly RULESET_NAME_TAG='dm-github-policy tag protection'
readonly CODE_SEC_CONFIG_NAME='dm-github-policy code security'

dry_run=0
verbose=0
mode='apply'   ## apply | audit

show_help() {
   cat <<'EOF'
Apply project-wide GitHub security/policy settings to the source
organizations (Kicksecure, Whonix). Idempotent and apply-only - never
disables a setting that was already on. Org-wide settings are
preferred over per-repo where possible: enabling a security feature
"for all existing repos" via a single org-level call beats iterating
every repo, both for atomicity and for new-repo coverage.

Usage:
  dm-github-policy             ## apply policy to Kicksecure + Whonix
  dm-github-policy --dry-run   ## report planned changes only
  dm-github-policy --audit     ## read-only inspection of current state
                               ## (current settings, members lacking
                               ## 2FA, existing rulesets); no writes
  dm-github-policy --help

Settings applied at the org level:
  - Fork-PR contributor approval = all_external_contributors
  - Default workflow GITHUB_TOKEN permissions = read; cannot
    create or approve pull requests
  - Allowed Actions = github-owned + Marketplace-verified-creators
    only
  - Members policy:
    * Default repository permission for new members = read
    * Members cannot create repositories (owners only)
  - 2FA enforcement (UI-only). The two_factor_requirement_enabled
    field is read-only on PATCH /orgs/{org}; toggle in the UI under
    Settings -> Authentication security.
    CAUTION: enabling removes members who do not have 2FA on. Run
    --audit first to see the list of members lacking 2FA.
  - Code security via the modern Code Security Configurations
    API: a single org-level configuration enables secret scanning,
    push protection, Dependabot alerts and security updates, and
    dependency graph. Attached to all existing repos (scope=all)
    and set as the default for newly created repos. CodeQL default
    setup and private vulnerability reporting are explicitly
    disabled in the configuration.
  - Repository ruleset on the default branch of all repos:
    block force-push, block deletion, require signed commits.
    bypass_actors=[] - no one, including org owners, can override.
    Deliberately does NOT include the pull_request rule (would
    require all merges to go through a PR; maintainers push
    directly to master), required_status_checks (per-repo CI
    coupling), or required_linear_history.
  - Repository ruleset on tags of all repos: block deletion,
    block re-pointing, require signed tags. Same bypass_actors=[].
  - PAT and App policy toggles: SKIPPED (UI-only; --audit reports
    state). Apply path prints UI links for manual configuration.

Settings applied per-repo (no org-wide endpoint):
  - has_wiki = false
  - has_issues = true

Deliberately NOT applied (with reasoning):
  - Private vulnerability reporting: project channel for disclosure
    is OpenPGP email; enabling GitHub's would split the inbox.
  - CodeQL default setup: brittle auto-detection; a committed
    .github/workflows/codeql.yml is more reliable. Belongs in a
    separate workflow-files-deploy tool.
  - Required PR reviews / status checks / linear history /
    web-commit-signoff / disable-forking: each has a real cost
    that does not justify uniform application.
  - Allowed Actions tightening can break existing workflows pinned
    to unverified third-party actions. Run --audit first to spot
    anything you'd need to update.

Note on signed commits + UI merging:
  GitHub's "Merge pull request" and "Squash and merge" buttons sign
  the produced commit with the web-flow GPG key, so they keep
  working. "Rebase and merge" does NOT re-sign rebased commits, so
  it will fail when a contributor's PR commits are unsigned.
  Prefer Merge or Squash for fork PRs.

Auth:
  $GITHUB_TOKEN env var, or chmod-600 ~/.config/github-token.
  Classic PAT needs admin:org + repo. Fine-grained PAT needs
  Administration r/w + Code security r/w + Webhooks r/w +
  Members r/w (the last for 2FA enforcement).

OSSF Scorecard mapping:
  Branch-Protection: Tier 1 (3/10) - deliberate ceiling. Higher
    tiers require switching from maintainer-direct-push to
    PR-required-for-merge, which conflicts with our model.
  Token-Permissions: covered (default workflow GITHUB_TOKEN=read,
    no PR approval).
  Webhooks (Critical): audit lists org-level webhooks lacking a
    secret. Per-repo webhooks not yet audited.
  Dangerous-Workflow (Critical): partially mitigated by
    Allowed-Actions=verified-only. Detection is per-workflow
    content; avoid pull_request_target with explicit PR checkout
    and avoid using untrusted github.event.* fields directly in
    inline scripts. Reference:
    https://securitylab.github.com/research/github-actions-preventing-pwn-requests/
  Code-Review (High): deliberately skipped. Maintainer-direct-push
    workflow.
  Vulnerabilities (High): covered indirectly via Dependabot alerts
    enabled by the code-security configuration.
  Dependency-Update-Tool (High): coverage requires a committed
    .github/dependabot.yml per repo (Scorecard checks file
    presence). Audit lists missing repos as a worklist.
  Signed-Releases (High): tag ruleset enforces signed tags;
    per-release artifact signing is build-time per repo.
  SAST / CodeQL (Medium): deliberately skipped at the API level
    (default-setup is brittle). A committed
    .github/workflows/codeql.yml is the better path; outside this
    tool's scope.
  Maintained (High): organic activity metric; not addressable by
    policy.
EOF
}

while [ "$#" -gt 0 ]; do
   case "$1" in
      --dry-run) dry_run=1; shift ;;
      --audit)   mode='audit'; shift ;;
      -v|--verbose) verbose=1; shift ;;
      -h|--help)
         show_help
         exit 0
         ;;
      *)
         printf 'unknown argument: %s\n' "$(ghorg_safe_print 64 "$1")" >&2
         exit 64
         ;;
   esac
done

ghorg_require_deps

## Per-run counter accumulator. main() creates a tempfile and exports
## its path; api_call and record_skip append a one-word status (ok |
## warn | dry | skip) per event. main() then sums by `wc -l` at the
## end. A tempfile (not in-memory variables) is required because the
## per-repo apply loop backgrounds children with `&`; bash variable
## updates in those subshells would be lost on join. Short appends
## from concurrent processes are atomic up to PIPE_BUF (4096 bytes on
## Linux) - our writes are 4-5 bytes.
api_counter_file=''

api_record() {
   [ -n "$api_counter_file" ] || return 0
   printf '%s\n' "$1" >> "$api_counter_file"
}

## Records a SKIP event. Used by apply_org_policy for settings that
## have no REST API (PAT, App, OAuth policies) and must be flipped in
## the UI.
record_skip() {
   api_record skip
}

## Wrapper that prints a one-line summary per HTTP call. On non-2xx
## the body is logged via sanitize-string and the call returns
## non-zero, but the caller decides whether to abort or continue.
##
## Success lines are printed unconditionally (not gated on -v) so the
## operator sees positive evidence that each setting was applied; the
## end-of-run summary then shows the totals.
api_call() {
   local label="$1" method="$2" path="$3" body="${4:-}"
   if [ "$dry_run" = '1' ]; then
      printf 'DRY-RUN: %s -> %s %s\n' "$label" "$method" "$path"
      api_record dry
      return 0
   fi
   local result status
   result="$(ghorg_api "$method" "$path" "$body")" || {
      api_record warn
      return 1
   }
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   case "$status" in
      200|201|204)
         printf 'ok:   %s [%s]\n' "$label" "$status"
         api_record ok
         return 0
         ;;
      *)
         printf 'warn: %s [%s]\n%s\n' "$label" "$status" \
            "$(ghorg_safe_print 512 "$(ghorg_body_of "$result")")" >&2
         api_record warn
         return 1
         ;;
   esac
}

## Idempotent ruleset upsert. GitHub's POST /orgs/{org}/rulesets
## creates a new ruleset every time, which would yield duplicates on
## re-run; use GET to find an existing ruleset by name and PUT to
## update, falling back to POST when none exists.
##
## Args: $1 = org, $2 = ruleset name (used for the GET-by-name match),
## $3 = JSON body (must include the same name).
upsert_org_ruleset() {
   local org="$1" name="$2" body="$3"
   if [ "$dry_run" = '1' ]; then
      printf 'DRY-RUN: %s: upsert ruleset %s\n' "$org" "$name"
      return 0
   fi

   local result status existing_id
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/rulesets")" || return 1
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   if [ "$status" != '200' ]; then
      printf 'warn: %s: list rulesets returned %s\n' "$org" "$status" >&2
      return 1
   fi
   existing_id="$(ghorg_body_of "$result" \
      | jq -r --arg name "$name" \
        '.[] | select(.name == $name) | .id' \
      | head --lines=1)"

   if [ -n "$existing_id" ] && [ "$existing_id" != "null" ]; then
      ## Validate id is numeric before placing it into a URL path.
      if ! [[ "$existing_id" =~ ^[0-9]+$ ]]; then
         printf 'warn: %s: ruleset id %s not numeric; refusing\n' \
            "$org" "$(ghorg_safe_print 32 "$existing_id")" >&2
         return 1
      fi
      api_call "${org}: update ruleset id=${existing_id} (${name})" \
         PUT "/orgs/${org}/rulesets/${existing_id}" "$body"
   else
      api_call "${org}: create ruleset (${name})" \
         POST "/orgs/${org}/rulesets" "$body"
   fi
}

## Idempotent code-security-configuration upsert + attach + default.
## Replaces the deprecated PATCH /orgs/{org} security-defaults fields
## and /orgs/{org}/{product}/enable_all endpoints with the modern
## /orgs/{org}/code-security/configurations API. Three steps per org:
##   1. find-or-create the configuration named CODE_SEC_CONFIG_NAME
##   2. attach it to all existing repos (scope=all)
##   3. set it as the default for new repos (default_for_new_repos=all)
##
## Configuration body: enables secret scanning + push protection,
## Dependabot alerts + security updates, dependency graph. Disables
## CodeQL default setup (brittle on monorepos - prefer a committed
## .github/workflows/codeql.yml) and private vulnerability reporting
## (project disclosure channel is OpenPGP email; see header notes).
apply_code_security_config() {
   local org="$1"

   local config_body
   config_body="$(jq -n --arg name "$CODE_SEC_CONFIG_NAME" '{
      name: $name,
      description: "Project-wide code security applied via dm-github-policy.",
      enforcement: "enforced",
      secret_scanning: "enabled",
      secret_scanning_push_protection: "enabled",
      dependabot_alerts: "enabled",
      dependabot_security_updates: "enabled",
      dependency_graph: "enabled",
      code_scanning_default_setup: "disabled",
      private_vulnerability_reporting: "disabled"
   }')"

   if [ "$dry_run" = '1' ]; then
      printf 'DRY-RUN: %s: upsert code-security configuration %s\n' \
         "$org" "$CODE_SEC_CONFIG_NAME"
      printf 'DRY-RUN: %s: attach code-security configuration scope=all\n' "$org"
      printf 'DRY-RUN: %s: set code-security configuration default_for_new_repos=all\n' "$org"
      api_record dry; api_record dry; api_record dry
      return 0
   fi

   ## Find existing configuration by name.
   local list_result list_status existing_id
   list_result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/code-security/configurations")" \
      || { api_record warn; return 1; }
   list_status="$(ghorg_status_of "$list_result")"
   if [ "$list_status" != '200' ]; then
      printf 'warn: %s: list code-security configurations [%s]\n%s\n' \
         "$org" "$list_status" \
         "$(ghorg_safe_print 512 "$(ghorg_body_of "$list_result")")" >&2
      api_record warn
      return 1
   fi
   existing_id="$(ghorg_body_of "$list_result" \
      | jq -r --arg name "$CODE_SEC_CONFIG_NAME" \
        '.[] | select(.name == $name) | .id' \
      | head --lines=1)"

   if [ -n "$existing_id" ] && [ "$existing_id" != 'null' ]; then
      if ! [[ "$existing_id" =~ ^[0-9]+$ ]]; then
         printf 'warn: %s: code-security config id %s not numeric; refusing\n' \
            "$org" "$(ghorg_safe_print 32 "$existing_id")" >&2
         api_record warn
         return 1
      fi
      api_call "${org}: update code-security configuration id=${existing_id}" \
         PATCH "/orgs/${org}/code-security/configurations/${existing_id}" \
         "$config_body" || true
   else
      ## POST returns the new config object including its id; we need
      ## the id for the attach + default calls.
      local create_result create_status
      create_result="$(ghorg_api POST "/orgs/${org}/code-security/configurations" "$config_body")" \
         || { api_record warn; return 1; }
      create_status="$(ghorg_status_of "$create_result")"
      case "$create_status" in
         200|201)
            existing_id="$(ghorg_body_of "$create_result" | jq -r '.id')"
            printf 'ok:   %s: created code-security configuration id=%s [%s]\n' \
               "$org" "$existing_id" "$create_status"
            api_record ok
            ;;
         *)
            printf 'warn: %s: create code-security configuration [%s]\n%s\n' \
               "$org" "$create_status" \
               "$(ghorg_safe_print 512 "$(ghorg_body_of "$create_result")")" >&2
            api_record warn
            return 1
            ;;
      esac
   fi

   ## Attach to all existing repos in the org. scope=all covers every
   ## repo without listing them; the configuration's enforcement field
   ## takes care of the on/off state.
   local attach_body
   attach_body="$(jq -n '{scope: "all"}')"
   api_call "${org}: attach code-security config to all repos" \
      POST "/orgs/${org}/code-security/configurations/${existing_id}/attach" \
      "$attach_body" || true

   ## Make this configuration the default for newly created repos.
   local default_body
   default_body="$(jq -n '{default_for_new_repos: "all"}')"
   api_call "${org}: set code-security config as default for new repos" \
      PUT "/orgs/${org}/code-security/configurations/${existing_id}/defaults" \
      "$default_body" || true
}

## Org-level settings: fork-PR approval, workflow permissions, allowed
## actions, 2FA SKIP, member policy, code-security configuration,
## branch and tag rulesets, PAT and App SKIPs.
apply_org_policy() {
   local org="$1"
   printf '\n=== org policy: %s ===\n' "$org"

   local body

   ## 1. Fork-PR contributor approval = all_external_contributors.
   body="$(jq -n '{approval_policy: "all_external_contributors"}')"
   api_call "${org}: fork-PR approval=all_external_contributors" \
      PUT "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions/fork-pr-contributor-approval" "$body" \
      || true

   ## 2. Default workflow GITHUB_TOKEN permissions = read; cannot
   ##    approve PRs. Covers the "default workflow permissions" and
   ##    "Allow Actions to create and approve pull requests" toggles
   ##    in the org Actions settings UI.
   body="$(jq -n '{
      default_workflow_permissions: "read",
      can_approve_pull_request_reviews: false
   }')"
   api_call "${org}: workflow GITHUB_TOKEN read-only, no PR approval" \
      PUT "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions/workflow" "$body" \
      || true

   ## 3. Allowed Actions = selected (github-owned + verified creators).
   ##    Two-step: first turn the org-level Actions permission to
   ##    "selected" (gating which actions can be invoked), then set the
   ##    selected-actions list to allow github-owned and verified.
   ##    CAUTION: a workflow that pins to an unverified third-party
   ##    action will start failing after this. Audit before applying
   ##    if you have not already; --dry-run shows what would change.
   body="$(jq -n '{
      enabled_repositories: "all",
      allowed_actions: "selected"
   }')"
   api_call "${org}: actions enabled=all, allowed=selected" \
      PUT "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions" "$body" \
      || true
   body="$(jq -n '{
      github_owned_allowed: true,
      verified_allowed: true,
      patterns_allowed: []
   }')"
   api_call "${org}: selected-actions = github-owned + verified-creators" \
      PUT "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions/selected-actions" "$body" \
      || true

   ## 4. Member-side org policy: default repo permission pinned to
   ##    "read", repository creation restricted to admins. Bundled
   ##    into one PATCH /orgs/{org} body.
   ##
   ##    Verified against the OpenAPI spec
   ##    (github/rest-api-description) at edit time:
   ##      - default_repository_permission: present
   ##      - members_can_create_repositories: present
   ##      - members_can_create_public_repositories: present
   ##      - members_can_create_private_repositories: present
   ##      - members_can_create_internal_repositories: present
   ##    Removed (not in spec or deprecated):
   ##      - members_allowed_repository_creation_type (DEPRECATED;
   ##        replaced by the granular members_can_create_*_repositories
   ##        booleans).
   ##      - members_can_delete_repositories (NOT in PATCH /orgs/{org}
   ##        schema; would be silently ignored. Restricting repo
   ##        deletion is UI-only as of verification).
   ##      - two_factor_requirement_enabled (READ-only field on the
   ##        GET /orgs/{org} response; not settable via PATCH. 2FA
   ##        enforcement is UI-only - see step 4b below).
   body="$(jq -n '{
      default_repository_permission: "read",
      members_can_create_repositories: false,
      members_can_create_public_repositories: false,
      members_can_create_private_repositories: false,
      members_can_create_internal_repositories: false
   }')"
   api_call "${org}: members policy (default-perm=read, no member create)" \
      PATCH "/orgs/${org}" "$body" \
      || true

   ## 4b. 2FA enforcement (UI-only).
   ##     two_factor_requirement_enabled is a READ-only field on GET
   ##     /orgs/{org}; the OpenAPI spec exposes no PATCH/PUT setter
   ##     for it. Print a SKIP with the UI URL so the operator knows
   ##     to flip it manually.
   ##     CAUTION: enabling 2FA in the UI on an org with members who
   ##     do not have 2FA turned on will REMOVE those members. The
   ##     --audit mode lists members lacking 2FA so the operator can
   ##     confirm membership state before flipping the switch.
   printf 'skip: %s: 2FA enforcement must be set via UI - see\n' "$org"
   printf '       https://github.com/organizations/%s/settings/security\n' "$org"
   record_skip

   ## 5+6. Code security via the modern Code Security Configurations
   ##      API (replaces the now-deprecated PATCH /orgs/{org} security
   ##      defaults fields and the /orgs/{org}/{product}/enable_all
   ##      family). Three calls per org:
   ##        a) upsert a configuration named CODE_SEC_CONFIG_NAME with
   ##           the desired feature toggles (idempotent: if a same-name
   ##           config exists, PATCH it; else POST).
   ##        b) attach the configuration to ALL existing repos
   ##           (scope=all). One call regardless of repo count.
   ##        c) set the configuration as the default for newly created
   ##           repos (default_for_new_repos=all).
   ##
   ##      Deliberately disabled in the configuration: code_scanning_default_setup
   ##      (CodeQL default setup is brittle - see header) and
   ##      private_vulnerability_reporting (project channel is OpenPGP
   ##      email - see header).
   apply_code_security_config "$org" || true

   ## 7. Org ruleset on the default branch of every repo: block force
   ##    pushes (non_fast_forward), block deletion, require signed
   ##    commits. ~DEFAULT_BRANCH applies to whichever branch each repo
   ##    has set as default; ~ALL covers every repo in the org.
   ##
   ##    bypass_actors is set to the empty list explicitly. Without an
   ##    actor in this list NO ONE - including org owners and repo
   ##    admins - can override the rules. This is stricter than the
   ##    legacy per-repo branch protection, where enforce_admins=false
   ##    would let admins force-push past the rule. Rulesets and
   ##    legacy branch protections layer additively (most restrictive
   ##    wins), so this also closes the bypass on any leftover legacy
   ##    branch protection rules from earlier runs.
   ##
   ##    DELIBERATELY OMITTED rule types:
   ##      - pull_request (would require all merges into the default
   ##        branch to go through a PR). Maintainers push directly to
   ##        master from the terminal; enabling this would cause the
   ##        "Bypassed rule violations: Changes must be made through a
   ##        pull request" warning on every legitimate push.
   ##      - required_status_checks (each repo would need a CI defined
   ##        and named here; not feasible to apply uniformly).
   ##      - required_linear_history (opinionated; can break some
   ##        merge workflows).
   local branch_ruleset
   branch_ruleset="$(jq -n --arg name "$RULESET_NAME_BRANCH" '{
      name: $name,
      target: "branch",
      enforcement: "active",
      bypass_actors: [],
      conditions: {
         ref_name: { include: ["~DEFAULT_BRANCH"], exclude: [] },
         repository_name: { include: ["~ALL"], exclude: [] }
      },
      rules: [
         { type: "deletion" },
         { type: "non_fast_forward" },
         { type: "required_signatures" }
      ]
   }')"
   upsert_org_ruleset "$org" "$RULESET_NAME_BRANCH" "$branch_ruleset" || true

   ## 8. Org ruleset for tags: block tag deletion, block tag
   ##    re-pointing (non_fast_forward), require signed tags. Critical
   ##    for release integrity - without this, anyone with push rights
   ##    could move a release tag like v1.0 to point at a different
   ##    commit. Same bypass_actors=[] enforcement: nobody, including
   ##    owners, can override.
   local tag_ruleset
   tag_ruleset="$(jq -n --arg name "$RULESET_NAME_TAG" '{
      name: $name,
      target: "tag",
      enforcement: "active",
      bypass_actors: [],
      conditions: {
         ref_name: { include: ["~ALL"], exclude: [] },
         repository_name: { include: ["~ALL"], exclude: [] }
      },
      rules: [
         { type: "deletion" },
         { type: "non_fast_forward" },
         { type: "required_signatures" }
      ]
   }')"
   upsert_org_ruleset "$org" "$RULESET_NAME_TAG" "$tag_ruleset" || true

   ## 9. Personal access token policies (audit-only path).
   ##    The org-level toggles "Allow access via fine-grained PATs",
   ##    "Require approval for fine-grained PATs", "Allow classic PATs",
   ##    "Restrict access by classic PATs" are configurable in the org
   ##    Settings UI under Personal access tokens. As of research, the
   ##    public REST API exposes GETs for pending requests and approved
   ##    PATs but does NOT expose stable setters for the policy
   ##    toggles. The apply path is therefore commented out below; the
   ##    audit path (--audit) lists pending requests and approved PATs
   ##    so the operator can see what is in flight before flipping the
   ##    toggles in the UI.
   ##
   ## TODO: replace with real API calls when GitHub publishes stable
   ## REST endpoints for the PAT policy toggles. Reference:
   ## https://github.com/orgs/${org}/settings/personal-access-tokens
   printf 'skip: %s: PAT policy toggles must be set via UI - see\n' "$org"
   printf '       https://github.com/organizations/%s/settings/personal-access-tokens\n' "$org"
   record_skip
   ## Sample of what would be set if a stable REST surface existed:
   # body="$(jq -n '{
   #    personal_access_token_classic_allowed: false,
   #    personal_access_token_fine_grained_approval_required: true
   # }')"
   # api_call "${org}: PAT policy (block classic, require approval)" \
   #    PATCH "/orgs/${org}" "$body" || true

   ## 10. GitHub App / OAuth App installation policies (audit-only).
   ##    "Restrict App installation to org owners", "Restrict OAuth
   ##    third-party access", "Require approval for new App installs"
   ##    are UI-only. REST exposes GETs for installed Apps but no
   ##    setters. The audit path lists installed Apps; the apply path
   ##    skips with a UI pointer.
   ##
   ## TODO: replace with real API calls when GitHub publishes stable
   ## REST endpoints. Reference:
   ## https://github.com/organizations/${org}/settings/oauth_application_policy
   ## https://github.com/organizations/${org}/settings/installations
   printf 'skip: %s: GitHub App / OAuth App policies must be set via UI - see\n' "$org"
   printf '       https://github.com/organizations/%s/settings/installations\n' "$org"
   printf '       https://github.com/organizations/%s/settings/oauth_application_policy\n' "$org"
   record_skip
   ## Sample of what would be set if a stable REST surface existed:
   # body="$(jq -n '{
   #    members_can_install_github_apps: false,
   #    oauth_app_access_restrictions_enabled: true
   # }')"
   # api_call "${org}: App install/OAuth restrictions" \
   #    PATCH "/orgs/${org}" "$body" || true
}

## One-line GET-and-print helper for audit_org_state. Args:
##   $1 = label, $2 = API path, $3 = jq filter (default '.').
audit_get() {
   local label="$1" path="$2" jq_filter="${3:-.}"
   local result status body
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "$path")" || {
      printf '  %s: <api error>\n' "$label"
      return 0
   }
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   if [ "$status" != '200' ]; then
      printf '  %s: HTTP %s\n' "$label" "$status"
      return 0
   fi
   body="$(ghorg_body_of "$result")"
   ## sanitize-string reads stdin natively, so the pipe is the
   ## sanitization step; ghorg_safe_print is for arg-form callers.
   printf '  %s: %s\n' "$label" "$(printf '%s' "$body" \
      | jq -r "$jq_filter" 2>/dev/null \
      | tr '\n' ' ' \
      | sanitize-string 200)"
}

## Read-only inspection of an org's current security/policy state.
## Does no PATCH/PUT/POST. Designed to be run before --apply so the
## operator can spot the two changes most likely to surprise them:
## an Allowed-Actions tightening that breaks workflows pinned to
## unverified third-party actions, and a 2FA enforcement that removes
## members without 2FA.
audit_org_state() {
   local org="$1"
   printf '\n=== audit: %s ===\n' "$org"

   audit_get 'fork-PR approval policy' \
      "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions/fork-pr-contributor-approval" \
      '.approval_policy // "(unset)"'

   audit_get 'workflow GITHUB_TOKEN permissions' \
      "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions/workflow" \
      '"default=" + (.default_workflow_permissions // "?") + ", can_approve_PRs=" + ((.can_approve_pull_request_reviews // false) | tostring)'

   ## Capture allowed_actions inline so we can decide whether the
   ## selected-actions endpoint is meaningful. GitHub returns 409 on
   ## /actions/permissions/selected-actions when allowed_actions is
   ## not "selected" - audit shouldn't print a noisy HTTP 409 for
   ## that expected case; it should print "(N/A)" with the reason.
   local _ap_result _ap_status _ap_body allowed_actions=''
   _ap_result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions")" || true
   _ap_status="$(ghorg_status_of "$_ap_result")"
   if [ "$_ap_status" = '200' ]; then
      _ap_body="$(ghorg_body_of "$_ap_result")"
      allowed_actions="$(printf '%s' "$_ap_body" | jq --raw-output '.allowed_actions // "?"')"
      printf '  actions allowed_actions: enabled_repos=%s, allowed_actions=%s\n' \
         "$(printf '%s' "$_ap_body" | jq --raw-output '.enabled_repositories // "?"')" \
         "$allowed_actions"
   else
      printf '  actions allowed_actions: HTTP %s\n' "$_ap_status"
   fi

   if [ "$allowed_actions" = 'selected' ]; then
      audit_get 'selected-actions allow-list' \
         "/orgs/${org}/actions/permissions/selected-actions" \
         '"github_owned=" + ((.github_owned_allowed // false) | tostring) + ", verified=" + ((.verified_allowed // false) | tostring) + ", patterns=" + ((.patterns_allowed // []) | length | tostring)'
   else
      printf '  selected-actions allow-list: (N/A while allowed_actions=%s)\n' \
         "${allowed_actions:-?}"
   fi

   audit_get '2FA required for org members' \
      "/orgs/${org}" \
      '.two_factor_requirement_enabled // false'

   audit_get 'code-security defaults for new repos' \
      "/orgs/${org}" \
      '"secret=" + ((.secret_scanning_enabled_for_new_repositories // false) | tostring) + ", push_prot=" + ((.secret_scanning_push_protection_enabled_for_new_repositories // false) | tostring) + ", dep_alerts=" + ((.dependabot_alerts_enabled_for_new_repositories // false) | tostring) + ", dep_updates=" + ((.dependabot_security_updates_enabled_for_new_repositories // false) | tostring) + ", dep_graph=" + ((.dependency_graph_enabled_for_new_repositories // false) | tostring)'

   ## Members without 2FA - the list that would be removed if 2FA
   ## enforcement were enabled. Paginate; stop after a sensible cap to
   ## avoid runaway output if the org has many such members.
   printf '  members lacking 2FA (would be removed by enforcement):\n'
   local result status body count names
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/members?filter=2fa_disabled&per_page=100")" || true
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   if [ "$status" = '200' ]; then
      body="$(ghorg_body_of "$result")"
      count="$(printf '%s' "$body" | jq 'length')"
      if [ "$count" = '0' ]; then
         printf '    (none)\n'
      else
         names="$(printf '%s' "$body" | jq -r '.[].login')"
         while IFS= read -r u; do
            [ -z "$u" ] && continue
            printf '    - %s\n' "$(ghorg_safe_print 64 "$u")"
         done <<< "$names"
      fi
   else
      printf '    HTTP %s (need admin:org / Members read scope)\n' "$status"
   fi

   ## Existing rulesets matching the names we'd upsert (branch + tag).
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/rulesets")" || true
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   if [ "$status" = '200' ]; then
      local ruleset_body name ids
      ruleset_body="$(ghorg_body_of "$result")"
      for name in "$RULESET_NAME_BRANCH" "$RULESET_NAME_TAG"; do
         printf '  existing rulesets named "%s":\n' "$name"
         ids="$(printf '%s' "$ruleset_body" \
            | jq -r --arg name "$name" \
              '.[] | select(.name == $name) | .id' || true)"
         if [ -z "$ids" ]; then
            printf '    (none; --apply would create one)\n'
         else
            while IFS= read -r id; do
               [ -z "$id" ] && continue
               printf '    - id=%s\n' "$(ghorg_safe_print 32 "$id")"
            done <<< "$ids"
         fi
      done
   else
      printf '  rulesets list: HTTP %s\n' "$status"
   fi

   ## Personal access tokens: count pending requests + count approved
   ## fine-grained PATs accessing the org. Both indicate the
   ## fine-grained PAT system is in active use, which is informative
   ## context for the operator deciding whether to flip the UI policy
   ## toggles (the toggles are not REST-settable - see apply_org_policy).
   printf '  fine-grained PAT activity:\n'
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/personal-access-token-requests?per_page=1")" || true
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   case "$status" in
      200)
         ## Count via the JSON length on this page; use a HEAD-style
         ## follow-up if exact totals matter (skipped for simplicity).
         local pending
         pending="$(ghorg_body_of "$result" | jq 'length' 2>/dev/null || printf '?')"
         printf '    pending requests on first page: %s\n' "$pending"
         ;;
      404|403)
         printf '    requests endpoint: HTTP %s (approval flow may be off / token lacks scope)\n' "$status"
         ;;
      *) printf '    requests endpoint: HTTP %s\n' "$status" ;;
   esac
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/personal-access-tokens?per_page=1")" || true
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   case "$status" in
      200)
         local approved
         approved="$(ghorg_body_of "$result" | jq 'length' 2>/dev/null || printf '?')"
         printf '    approved tokens on first page: %s\n' "$approved"
         ;;
      *) printf '    approved tokens endpoint: HTTP %s\n' "$status" ;;
   esac

   ## Installed GitHub Apps. List names so operator can verify the set
   ## is the intended one before deciding whether to lock down installs.
   printf '  installed GitHub Apps:\n'
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/installations?per_page=100")" || true
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   if [ "$status" = '200' ]; then
      local installs
      installs="$(ghorg_body_of "$result" \
         | jq -r '.installations[]? | "    - " + (.app_slug // "?") + " (id=" + ((.id // 0) | tostring) + ")"' \
         2>/dev/null || true)"
      if [ -z "$installs" ]; then
         printf '    (none)\n'
      else
         while IFS= read -r line; do
            [ -z "$line" ] && continue
            printf '%s\n' "$line"
         done <<< "$installs"
      fi
   else
      printf '    HTTP %s\n' "$status"
   fi

   ## Org webhooks: any without a configured `secret` are a Critical
   ## risk per the OSSF Scorecard "Webhooks" check. The GitHub API
   ## never returns the secret value itself; presence is reflected as
   ## a non-empty placeholder in `.config.secret`. Absent or empty
   ## means no secret configured - the webhook accepts unauthenticated
   ## payloads.
   printf '  org webhooks (Scorecard "Webhooks" check):\n'
   result="$(ghorg_api GET "/orgs/${org}/hooks?per_page=100")" || true
   status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
   if [ "$status" = '200' ]; then
      local total no_secret
      total="$(ghorg_body_of "$result" | jq 'length' 2>/dev/null || printf '?')"
      no_secret="$(ghorg_body_of "$result" \
         | jq '[.[] | select(.config.secret == null or .config.secret == "")] | length' \
         2>/dev/null || printf '?')"
      if [ "$total" = '0' ]; then
         printf '    (none configured)\n'
      else
         printf '    total=%s, lacking secret=%s\n' "$total" "$no_secret"
      fi
   else
      printf '    HTTP %s (token may lack admin:org_hook scope)\n' "$status"
   fi

   ## Dependabot config-file presence: the OSSF Scorecard
   ## "Dependency-Update-Tool" check looks for .github/dependabot.yml
   ## file presence specifically, so even though our org-level code-
   ## security config enables Dependabot alerts, repos missing the
   ## file still fail Scorecard. This audit counts repos with vs
   ## without and lists the missing ones as a worklist.
   printf '  dependabot.yml presence (Scorecard "Dependency-Update-Tool"):\n'
   local repos missing_count have_count missing_list
   repos="$(ghorg_list_repos "$org" 0 0 0 | sort --unique)"
   if [ -z "$repos" ]; then
      printf '    (no public non-archived non-fork repos)\n'
   else
      missing_count=0
      have_count=0
      missing_list=''
      while IFS= read -r repo; do
         [ -z "$repo" ] && continue
         result="$(ghorg_api GET "/repos/${org}/${repo}/contents/.github/dependabot.yml")" || true
         status="$(ghorg_status_of "$result")"
         if [ "$status" = '200' ]; then
            have_count=$(( have_count + 1 ))
         else
            missing_count=$(( missing_count + 1 ))
            missing_list+="    - ${org}/${repo}"$'\n'
         fi
      done <<< "$repos"
      printf '    have=%s, missing=%s\n' "$have_count" "$missing_count"
      if [ -n "$missing_list" ]; then
         printf '%s' "$missing_list"
      fi
   fi
}

## Per-repo settings - only the ones with no org-wide alternative.
## With the org-level rulesets and enable_all calls in apply_org_policy,
## the per-repo loop has shrunk to wiki-off / issues-on (these have no
## "apply to all repos" org endpoint).
apply_repo_policy() {
   local owner="$1" repo="$2"
   ghorg_validate_name "$owner" user || return 1
   ghorg_validate_name "$repo"  repo || return 1

   local patch
   patch="$(jq -n '{has_wiki: false, has_issues: true}')"
   api_call "${owner}/${repo}: wiki=off, issues=on" \
      PATCH "/repos/${owner}/${repo}" "$patch" || true
}

main() {
   local org repos
   if [ "$mode" = 'audit' ]; then
      for org in "${ORGS[@]}"; do
         audit_org_state "$org"
      done
      return 0
   fi

   ## Set up the tally tempfile before any api_call runs. Children
   ## from the per-repo parallel loop inherit api_counter_file via
   ## environment so their api_record appends land in the same file.
   api_counter_file="$(mktemp)"
   export api_counter_file
   trap 'rm -f -- "$api_counter_file"' EXIT

   for org in "${ORGS[@]}"; do
      apply_org_policy "$org"

      printf '\n=== repo policy: %s ===\n' "$org"
      ## Public, non-archived, non-fork repos. The org-level enable_all
      ## endpoints already cover security products on every repo; this
      ## loop is just for has_wiki / has_issues which have no org-wide
      ## API.
      repos="$(ghorg_list_repos "$org" 0 0 0 | sort -u)"
      if [ -z "$repos" ]; then
         printf 'no repos matched in %s\n' "$org" >&2
         continue
      fi

      local active=0
      while IFS= read -r repo; do
         [ -z "$repo" ] && continue
         apply_repo_policy "$org" "$repo" &
         active=$(( active + 1 ))
         if [ "$active" -ge "$POLICY_JOBS" ]; then
            wait -n || true
            active=$(( active - 1 ))
         fi
      done <<< "$repos"
      wait
   done

   ## End-of-run summary. Each api_call / record_skip appended one
   ## line per event; sum by status.
   local n_ok n_warn n_dry n_skip
   n_ok="$(  grep --count -- '^ok$'   "$api_counter_file" 2>/dev/null || true)"
   n_warn="$(grep --count -- '^warn$' "$api_counter_file" 2>/dev/null || true)"
   n_dry="$( grep --count -- '^dry$'  "$api_counter_file" 2>/dev/null || true)"
   n_skip="$(grep --count -- '^skip$' "$api_counter_file" 2>/dev/null || true)"
   ## grep returns "" when the file is empty; normalize to 0.
   n_ok="${n_ok:-0}"; n_warn="${n_warn:-0}"
   n_dry="${n_dry:-0}"; n_skip="${n_skip:-0}"

   printf '\n=== summary ===\n'
   printf '  ok:      %s\n' "$n_ok"
   printf '  warn:    %s\n' "$n_warn"
   printf '  dry-run: %s\n' "$n_dry"
   printf '  skip:    %s   (UI-only; see "skip:" lines above)\n' "$n_skip"
   printf '\ndone.\n'

   ## Non-zero exit if anything went wrong, so callers (cron, CI) can
   ## react. dry-run + skip are not failures.
   if [ "$n_warn" -gt 0 ]; then
      return 1
   fi
}

main
